# tags-explained.tflw — SPEC §4.1: `@tag`s above a `test` (or a `with each` block) filter which
# tests run via `tflw run --tag <name>`. A test can carry more than one tag; `--tag` matches any
# test that has it, regardless of what else it's tagged with. Try: `npx tflw run --tag examples`
# (every test in this whole examples/ directory, since each file tags its tests `@examples`),
# or `npx tflw run --tag smoke` (just the first test below).
#
# M29: `--tag a,b,c` (M17, comma-separated, whitespace-tolerant, OR semantics — "everything tagged
# a OR b OR c") composes with `--only` as AND, same as a single `--tag` value always has. The two
# tests below already demonstrate this without any extra DSL content needed (the composition is a
# CLI-argument-parsing feature, not something a test file's own content changes): `npx tflw run
# tests/examples/tags-explained.tflw --tag smoke,slow` matches *both* tests (the union), while
# `--tag smoke` alone matches only the first and `--tag slow` alone matches only the second.

@examples @smoke
test "tagged @examples and @smoke — matched by either --tag examples or --tag smoke"
  api GET /health
  expect status equals 200

@examples @slow
test "tagged @examples and @slow — matched by --tag examples or --tag slow, not --tag smoke"
  api GET /health
  expect status equals 200
